caption: Visited here for the exhibition and food festival. It was great and so much fun. The receptionist girl was very friendly and kindly informative and helpful. Will coming back later for more events!
Beautiful exhibit space -amazing light via 19th century steel glass roof. Saw Paris’s first Urban Art Fair. So much beautiful work in various media.

Attended the Paris Cafe Festival last weekend (9-10 March) in this lovely building. Perfect place for trade shows and exhibitions with the large skylights offering protection from the elements while allowing in the lovely light.

Antique-ish looking, glass roof-top warehouse building.  It is pretty big and housed the 2019 Urban Art Fair .  The Art fair was amazing with super talented artists from around the world.  I had a lot of favorite pieces and but the bronze sculptor of the elephant with buildings on its back was spectacular.

This former clothing market now converted to a place for exhibition. Currently there is a special art event, not open to general public trade only.

With its glass roof that allows the natural light flow into the building Carreau de Temple makes a nice place for exhibitions. Originally constructed as a market place, it now serves as a space to host conferences, exhibitions, recording studio and much more. It is situated in the heart of Paris and is easily accessible. Lively neighbourhood with parks and cafes definitely helps to attract the  visitors.

The Carreau du Temple gets its name from the nearby location of the medieval Knights Templar enclosure (which also functioned as a holding pen for Marie Antoinette et al during the French Revolution). In the 1950s, the building's covered arcades were the site of a thriving second-hand clothes market – but time and supermarkets had their way, and the venue fell into disuse before being earmarked for restoration by the council in 2001. Four hundred locals were involved in the project – after all, as then-Mayor Bertrand Delanoë put it, ‘The site belongs to them.’ After much brainstorming and bureaucratic faffing about, the arcades have reopened as a multi-purpose centre for sport, culture and food.  #theexpat
